To generate the swagger document for an OData endpoint with the permitted query options (e.g. Skip), you need to have the EnableQueryAttribute set on the method. This, alone, does not apply the query filters to Entity Framework. Instead, it has the data layer retrieve *all* records and then applies the filter to the outgoing response. Ideally, the filters would be applied to the Entity Framework query to retrieve only those records needed to satisfy the request. Instead, if you use ODataQueryOptions as a parameter in your endpoint, you *can* apply the request filters to Entity Framework but the EnableQueryAttribute then re-applies the filters to the outgoing request.


e.g. The following will retrieve all the records from a database call and then apply the &quot;skip&quot; record filter but properly generates the swagger document:
```
[EnableQuery(AllowedQueryOptions = AllowedQueryOptions.Top | AllowedQueryOptions.Skip)]
public async Task&lt;IActionResult&gt; GetReadings(Guid key, ODataFilterOptions&lt;MyItem&gt; options) {
 return options.ApplyTo(DbContext.MyItems);
}
```

If there are 18 results in your database and you supply &#39;10&#39; for the skip option, the results will be empty (the DB call filters the first 10 in the database call, then the EnableQuery attribute filters an additional 10 out of the outgoing request, leaving you with 0 results in the calling client).


The following allows you to apply the ODataFilterOptions to the EntityFramework call, but will not generate the proper swagger document to generate client code from:
```
public async Task&lt;IActionResult&gt; GetReadings(Guid key, ODataFilterOptions&lt;MyItem&gt; options) {
 return options.ApplyTo(DbContext.MyItems);
}
```



